A graphical bar (think bar charts) displayed in each cell. The length of the bar is related to the cell’s value.
An object created using drawing tools or commands.
Any temporary storage space used within or in conjunction with a computer, such as RAM or a USB flash drive.
A reference to data stored in a document from another program.
Referring to anything that is ready for immediate use by a user or application.
The timing and sequence of tasks within a project.
The block of filled-in cells that includes the currently selected cell or cells. The region extends in all directions to the first empty row or column.
An on-screen scale marked off in inches or other units of measure and used to show line widths, tab settings, paragraph indents, and so on.

The process of starting or resetting a computer or a device. When first turned on (cold boot) or reset (warm boot), the computer runs the software that loads and starts the computer's operating system, which prepares it for use.
A collection of email addresses that is treated as a single recipient for email distribution purposes, and that is created by and available to an individual Outlook user.
The first row in a spreadsheet. The header row contains category labels that describe the contents of the columns.
A command that will use a print driver installed by OneNote to create an image of a wide variety of filetypes. Files are printed to the print driver and inserted as images into OneNote.
Text displayed by Web browsers during image downloads for users who have graphics turned off, and for users who rely on screen-reading software to convert graphics on the screen to spoken words.
The menu option that displays the folders available in a user's mailbox.
A data type used in some programming languages, notably C, to declare variables that can store floating-point numbers.
To extend over and cover a part of something.
A graphic map that can document procedures, analyze processes, indicate work or information flow, or track cost and efficiency.
A pictorial graphic such as a digital photograph or illustration.
Properties, such as title, subject, and author, that are stored with each data access page.
Pertaining to a type of layout consisting of a collection of “Row-Wise Groupings”. A stacked layout most resembles a form with name/value pairs (label, textbox).
A workbook that is configured to allow multiple users on a network to view and make changes at the same time. Each user who saves the workbook sees the changes that are made by other users.

The process of viewing and updating the actual progress of tasks so that you can see progress across time, evaluate slippage of tasks, compare scheduled or baseline data to actual data, and check the completion percentage of tasks and your project.
A line added to a chart that makes it easier to view and evaluate data.
A formula that checks whether a given value is valid for a particular field.
To change a system or a data file to make it more current.
The Microsoft Office Web application that provides secure access to email, personal calendar, group scheduling, and collaboration applications on Microsoft Exchange Server with only a Web browser.
A property that defines valid input values for a field or record in a table, or a control on a form.
Able to be both read from and written to.
The ability for two or more software applications to work together with little effort from the user.
A control designed to contain content such as placeholder or sample text or images that is updated by the user, or pre-defined lists of items from which users can select.
A control that allows users to digitally sign a form or document.
A list of entities such as people, groups, or organizations with whom users communicate.
A visual effect that colors, tweaks, or otherwise graphically alters fonts.
A view on a calendar that displays items such as meetings and events from left to right on a time scale and that can incorporate items from multiple calendars.
To modify the value of a property or attribute.
An individual box or button with which users enter information on an electronic form.
A feature that enables the user to compact or collapse rows when viewing several levels of data.
To change between states or modes.
Row or column labels that are printed at the top of or on the left side of every page on a printed worksheet.

A table inserted within a table cell. If you use a table to lay out a page, and you want to use another table to arrange the information, you can insert a nested table.
A meaningful shorthand that makes it easier to understand the purpose of a cell reference, constant, formula, or table, each of which may be difficult to comprehend at first glance.
A portable computer that combines a processor, screen, and keyboard in a single case. The screen folds down onto the keyboard when not in use.
The vertical bar at the right of a window that users can click to move through a document.
The vertical bar at the right of a window that users can click to move through a document.
A menu item with options that can be applied to a file before it is shared with others (e.g. 'Mark as Final' or 'Add a Digital Signature').
The vertical reference line on a grid, chart, or graph that has horizontal and vertical dimensions.
A window that displays a form to either show or accept data. Form view is the primary means of adding and modifying data in tables. You cannot change the design of a form in this view.

A plastic (credit card–sized or smaller) device with an embedded microprocessor and a small amount of storage that is used, with an access code, to enable certificate-based authentication. Smart cards securely store certificates, public and private keys, passwords, and other types of personal information.
A color that that is currently selected for drawing or displaying text on the screen.
A data-entry field on a page. A site visitor supplies information in a field either by typing text or by selecting a field.
The value of a scorecard element in relation to the values of other elements of the same type.
The Office feature that automatically corrects errors and makes other substitutions as soon as a user types text.
A condition in which paper is blocked in the printing path of a printer, scanner, photocopier or fax machine.
A type of expansion board on PC-compatible computers that allows the playback and recording of sound, such as from a WAV or MIDI file or a music CD-ROM. Most PCs sold at retail include a sound card.
A type of expansion board on PC-compatible computers that allows the playback and recording of sound, such as from a WAV or MIDI file or a music CD-ROM. Most PCs sold at retail include a sound card.

All elements included in the Query window, such as tables, criteria, the order in which fields are arranged, and so on. The design also specifies whether Auto Query is turned on, and whether you can edit the source data.
A pane that lists all the fields in the underlying record source or database object.
A format consisting of ASCII codes in which database, spreadsheet, and similar documents can be structured to facilitate their use by and transfer to other programs.
A global template that you can use for any type of document. You can modify this template to change the default document formatting or content.
A menu that shows only basic commands and commands that you use often.
A marker that can be associated with content or items, such as photos or text, to identify certain types of information, and that allows users to find, view, and sort marked content.
The tool that allows the user to configure auto-replies.
Pertaining to time when an individual has nothing scheduled and appears as available.
A presentation within a presentation in which you group slides in an existing presentation so that you can show that section of the presentation to a particular audience.
A logical structure that organizes the members of a set into parent-child relationships.
A feature that allows various mathematical symbols to be entered using the keyboard.
A sequence of activities, actions, or tasks through which documents or items are passed as part of an automated business process.
To verify, test or control by comparison or examination.
Pertaining to a mixture of characters that are read from left to right and characters that are read from right to left.
The name of a category of information in a mail-merge data source. For example, "City," "State," and "PostalCode" are commonly used field names in an address list.
The slide that stores information about the design template applied, including font styles, placeholder sizes and positions, background design, and color schemes.
A group of OneNote sections.
The arrangement of text and graphics on the page of a document.
A graphic representation of trends in data series, such as a line sloping upward to represent increased sales over a period of months.

The menu for a group of ready-made shapes that includes basic shapes, such as rectangles and circles, plus a variety of lines and connectors, block arrows, flowchart symbols, stars and banners, and callouts.
The Windows program that collects and displays for users the system-level features of the computer, including hardware and software setup and configuration.
Pertaining to tasks that need to be done.
To transfer a file from one location to another where once the transfer is complete, there is only one copy of the file, in the new location.
Instructions that make hardware work.
A user who creates or edits a document.
A supported source of data that can be modeled by Business Connectivity Services, such as a database, Web service, or custom .NET Framework assembly.
The collection of custom properties for a shape.
In information processing, an operation performed by the computer at hand rather than by a remote computer.
A device capable of processing information, storing data, and producing a desired result based on instructions provided.
A visual effect that imparts a quality of translucency to windows.
Data that consists of characters representing the words and symbols of human speech.

A hidden file on the hard disk that Windows uses to hold parts of programs and data files that do not fit in memory. The paging file and physical memory, or random access memory (RAM), comprise virtual memory. Windows moves data from the paging file to memory as needed and moves data from memory to the paging file to make room for new data.

A hidden file on the hard disk that Windows uses to hold parts of programs and data files that do not fit in memory. The paging file and physical memory, or random access memory (RAM), comprise virtual memory. Windows moves data from the paging file to memory as needed and moves data from memory to the paging file to make room for new data.

A hidden file on the hard disk that Windows uses to hold parts of programs and data files that do not fit in memory. A control used on a form, report, or data access page to display or modify data from a table, query, or SQL statement.

An add-in that stores macros, AutoText entries, and custom toolbar, menu, and shortcut key settings that you can use while you work with documents based on any template. By default, the Normal template is a global template.
The approximate location of one or more resources, such as a person, computer, printer, or asset, in a space plan.
A type of flowchart that shows the relationship between a business process and the functional units (such as departments) responsible for that process.
A location on the horizontal ruler that indicates how far to indent text or where to begin a column of text.

Symbols in legends that show the patterns and colors assigned to the data series (or categories) in a chart. Legend keys appear to the left of legend entries. Formatting a legend key also formats the data marker that's associated with it.
A built-in format that can be applied to a range of data, or to controls and sections in a form or report to change their appearance.
A variety of graphics tablet that uses pressure sensors, rather than the electromagnetics used in more expensive high-resolution tablets, to track the position of a device on its surface.
The Outlook pane that can be enabled to show an overview of the user's schedule, tasks and frequent contacts.
A combination of paper and page settings that determines the way items print.
A cell that contains a formula that refers to another cell. For example, if cell D10 contains the formula =B5, cell D10 is a dependent of cell B5.
To replace existing characters with newly typed characters.
The small, upward-pointing symbol (^) typically found over the 6 key on the top row of a microcomputer keyboard.
A single cell that is created by combining two or more selected cells. The cell reference for a merged cell is the upper-left cell in the original selected range.

The Web browser–based interface of Microsoft Office Project that project team members and stakeholders can use to access and update information stored in Microsoft Project Server, without having to install Microsoft Project on their computers.
A domain controller that holds a copy of the global catalog for the forest.
Pertaining to an area restricted to a short distance from a reference point.
The degree of confidentiality of an email message or calendar item, ranging from normal to confidential.
A number between 1 and 53 that is assigned to each week of the year, where the first week of the year is the first week that contains a Thursday.
A ready-made button that the user can insert into his/her presentation and define hyperlinks for.
A postal address at which a person is normally resident.
The small calendar that displays the current month in Calendar and that provides a quick and easy way to move appointments and to view other dates.
Formatting applied to a heading. Microsoft Office Word has nine different built-in styles: Heading 1 through Heading 9.
A set of intersecting lines or linear elements at right angles to each other.
The process of using a tablet pen to create drawings or handwriting.
A rectangle that represents an imported graphic in your document. You can increase scrolling speed by temporarily replacing graphics with picture placeholders.

independent attributes associated with items, or members, in an OLAP cube. For example, if city items have size and population properties stored in the server cube, a PivotTable report can display the size and population of each city.

One of a number of separately printed parts of an oversized publication, such as a banner or poster, that cannot be printed as a single sheet. Separate tiles can be assembled to recreate the whole publication.
The folder that contains any .one files that have been sent to you as an email message attachment.
To transfer into a store or storage location.
In 2-D line charts, lines that extend from the highest to the lowest value in each category. High-low lines are often used in stock charts.
To retain a physical representation of (data or instructions) that enables them to be subsequently retrieved.
Text that does not fit within a text box. The text is hidden until it can be flowed into a new text box, or until the text box it overflows is resized to include it.
An association between two tables in which the primary key value of each record in the primary table corresponds to the value in the matching field or fields of many records in the related table.
The direction a publication will be printed on a sheet of paper. You can choose either portrait, which is the taller-than-wide orientation, or landscape, which is the wider-than-tall orientation.
The .pst data file used as the main delivery location for your email messages.
To confirm either that a result is correct or that a procedure or sequence of operations has been performed.

A handle (often, a tall, thin rectangle) that appears on a rebar or command band. By touching and dragging a gripper bar with a stylus or mouse, a user can reposition or resize a rebar or command band.
The option that allows the user to specify the intervals at which an appointment or task will be repeated.
In word processors and other applications, the feature that formats a document for printing but displays it on the video monitor rather than sending it directly to the printer.
A short horizontal line used as a punctuation mark.

A domain controller that holds the infrastructure operations master role in Active Directory. The infrastructure master updates the group-to-user reference whenever group memberships change and replicates these changes across the domain. At any time, the infrastructure master role can be assigned to only one domain controller in each domain.
The certification authority which issued the certificate to the subject.

Vertical lines appearing next to text that has been added, deleted, or changed by using tracked changes. You can specify that changed lines appear to the left or right of text. You can also hide changed lines.
The meaning of data as it is intended to be interpreted by people.
A feature that notifies a user when there is a change to posted content, workflow status, or when other user-defined criteria are met.
A non-printing line or point that can be used to help position or align objects or text.
The process of reconciling the differences between data stored in one location and a copy of the same data stored in another location.
The process of reconciling the differences between data stored in one location and a copy of the same data stored in another location.
The distance between the cells of a table or workbook.
A table, chart, graphic, equation, or other form of information.
A document that contains the header row (or header record) to be used with the data source specified for a mail-merge main document.
A paper size of 95.25mm x 171.45 mm.
To retrieve a writable copy of a file or project from a source repository. This locks the file for editing to prevent others from overwriting or editing it inadvertently.
A number that is not a whole number, such as ½ (vulgar fraction) or 0.5 (decimal fraction), formed by dividing one quantity into another.
A domain controller that has been assigned one or more special roles in an Active Directory domain.

A worksheet view that displays the areas to be printed and the locations of page breaks. The area to be printed is displayed in white, automatic page breaks appear as dashed lines, and manual page breaks appear as solid lines.
A set of software functionality designed to solve a specific problem or to provide a new functionality to the user.
The legal agreement between Microsoft and the user, with regard to the terms of use and transfer of software.
Used by Microsoft Exchange to identify, locate, and open a form.
Any ink that you add to a file that is not recognized as handwriting.

The Outlook add-in that enables small business owners to list business contacts, accounts, and opportunities, and to perform several tasks related to managing and tracking information about the business.
A field you can create. A custom field can be a blank, combination, or formula field.
A graphic element on a drawing that is associated with data.
A list of the captions for pictures, charts, graphs, slides, or other illustrations in a document, along with the numbers of the pages the captions appear on.
To perform the basic mathematical operation of deducting something from something else.
A collection of masters associated with a particular Visio drawing type, or template. By default, stencils that open with a template are docked on the left side of the drawing window.

A component database architecture that provides efficient network and Internet access to many types of data sources, including relational data, mail files, flat files, and spreadsheets. OLE DB comprises a specialized set of COM interfaces that expose data from a variety of data stores, both relational and nonrelational.
An animation effect that specifies how the display changes as a user moves from one item (such as a slide or Web page) to another.
A feature that serves as a launching point for several optional Windows tasks and OEM-defined tasks.
Displacement of the left or right edge of a block of text in relation to the margin or to other blocks of text.
An object (such as a customer, item, or employee) that shares a set of defined attributes or characteristics, and that is used to manage rules for data.
An object (such as a customer, item, or employee) that shares a set of defined attributes or characteristics, and that is used to manage rules for data.
As one aspect of a KPI, the desired level of performance with respect to a specific business goal or strategy. Actual values are evaluated against the target to determine KPI score and status.
The horizontal reference line on a grid, chart, or graph that has horizontal and vertical dimensions.
The horizontal reference line on a grid, chart, or graph that has horizontal and vertical dimensions.
A list that allows you to block a language encoding or character set in order to filter out unwanted international email messages that display in a language you don't understand.
A short piece of content that is informative but not essential.

The process of changing the values in cells to see how those changes affect the outcome of formulas on a worksheet. For example, varying the interest rate that is used in an amortization table to determine the amount of the payments.
A computer desktop area that extends across all displays that are connected to a computer.
A physical item for sale or purchase or available for license.
To change the size of an element on the screen.
To put new data in the place of other data, usually after conducting a search for the data to be replaced. Text-based applications such as word processors typically include Find and Replace commands.

The basic structure of a view. When you create a view, you must first select one of five view types (table, timeline, day/week/month, card, or icon) to determine how information will be arranged and formatted in your new view.
A descriptive text string that identifies a page.
An individual who sends an electronic message.
Pertaining to characters that are formatted to appear darker and heavier than the surrounding text.

A feature that enables records managers to create and manage entries to a “Holds list” such that any document, image, or webpage on that list cannot be deleted, modified, or allowed to expire until the item is removed from the list. The feature is typically used for items that are subject to events such as litigation, audits, or investigations.
The status applied to blocks of time in a user's Calendar to indicate that the user will be away.
A security feature that monitors programs on a computer to determine if they use system memory safely.
A security feature that monitors programs on a computer to determine if they use system memory safely.
A printed page that displays author notes beneath the slide that the notes accompany.

A pane that displays document property information for Word, Excel, and PowerPoint files stored in a WSS library. The pane is displayed below the ribbon and is actually a hosted custom InfoPath form. Information is synced automatically between the document and the WSS library.
A predefined combination of grouped and sorted messages in table view.

A list that includes the name of the person who originally sent a task request plus the names of everyone who received the task request, reassigned the task to someone else, or chose to keep an updated copy of the task in their task list.
An IP address of the OneNote session that is being shared with other users.
To place a file or project back in a source repository. This releases the lock for editing and enables other users to view the updated file or check out the file.

The pane at the bottom of the Calendar module where tasks are displayed. Tasks that are completed on a particular day "stick" to the day and are shown as a record of what work was performed on that day. Tasks not completed roll over to the next day and accumulate until completed.
A note alongside the main text that contains interesting or useful information.
A sequence of averages computed from parts of a data series for a specified period. In a chart, a moving average smooths the fluctuations in data, thus showing the pattern or trend more clearly.

A spreadsheet that contains information about a shape; for example, its dimensions, angle, and center of rotation and the styles that determine the shape's appearance.
The process of breaking a word between syllables at the end of a line or to separate the parts of a compound word.
A session in which multiple users can work together and see each other’s changes immediately.

The propagation of properties via InfoPath forms from the underlying data into named properties in Outlook or SharePoint sites. Promoted properties are used to group, filter, and sort data, files, and folders.
In an organization chart, a shape that is placed above and connected to any other shape, such as an employee (subordinate or coworker shape) or assistant shape.
A collection of files, managed by a manifest.xml file, that add functionality to a Microsoft Office Word or Microsoft Office Excel document by specifying custom display or actions.
A person whose work or profession is management.
To activate something making it available for use.
A numeric value that corresponds to a particular character in a set.
A OneNote item that has been marked with a note tag.
Software that fulfills the deliberately harmful intent of an attacker when run.
Software that fulfills the deliberately harmful intent of an attacker when run.
A symbol that is displayed beside a paragraph in outline view. You can use the symbol to display or hide subordinate levels of text and to reorganize text quickly.
To send a received content either modified or in its entirety, to a new recipient.
The portion of an on-screen file that has been marked as subject to user action.
A computer that provides shared resources, such as files or printers, to network users.
The sheet that you're working on in a workbook. The name on the tab of the active sheet is bold.
A setting in which existing characters are replaced with newly typed characters.

A testing process that supplies structured but invalid input to software application programming interfaces (APIs) and network interfaces to maximize the likelihood of detecting errors that might lead to software vulnerabilities.
Part of the Office Center feature that allows users to set various security and privacy options, and to see currently enforced security and privacy rules.
A handheld portable telephone that operates through a radio network.
A commercial organization.
The list or table that's used to create a PivotTable or PivotChart report. Source data can be taken from an Excel list or range, an external database or cube, or another PivotTable report.
To add a digital signature to a macro or file.
One character (or more) that is slightly higher than other text on a line, such as a footnote reference mark.
A diagramming capability that shows charts in three dimensions.

Any shape that you draw by using the Curve, Freeform, and Scribble tools. Freeform shapes can include straight lines and freehand curves. They can be drawn opened or closed and can be edited by using the drawing tools.

Paragraph formatting you can use to assign a hierarchical level (Level 1 through Level 9) to paragraphs in your document. For example, after you assign outline levels, you can work with the document in outline view or in the Document Map.
A symbol used to represent the Control key on the keyboard. For example, ^Z means "hold the Control key down and press the Z key."
The data type that holds a maximum of 8,000 characters.
An interactive technology in Microsoft Excel or Access that can show dynamic views of the same data from a list or a database.
Confidence in the reliability of an entity or service and the information that it provides.
An automated tool that helps find and fix specific problems on your computer.

An email security feature used to request confirmation that a message was received unaltered and information about who opened the message and when it was opened. This verification information is returned as a message to your Inbox.

The part of the Microsoft Office user interface above the main work area that presents commands and options to the user. The Ribbon replaced menus and toolbars starting in the 2007 Microsoft Office system.
An indent where the text is displaced into the left margin if text direction is set to left-to-right, or toward the right margin if text direction is set to right-to-left.
A Web page editor command that inserts a horizontal line onto a Web page.

A page that contains the design and layout elements that you want to repeat on multiple pages in a publication. Using master pages for these common elements gives your publication a more consistent appearance.
A box with dotted borders in a slide layout that holds title and body text or objects such as charts, tables, and pictures.
A query that retrieves data stored on your intranet or the Internet.
A predefined or free-form figure — such as a line, oval, cube, flowchart symbol, banner, or free-form scribble — that the user can insert into a document and then customize.
Pertaining to an operator that can hold an arbitrary number of arguments, or to a function that can hold an arbitrary number of operators.
Capable of being retrieved (read), printed or copied but not changed (written) or saved.
A field defined in a query that displays the result of an expression rather than displaying stored data. The value is recalculated each time a value in the expression changes.

The condition at a particular time of any of numerous elements of computing--a device, a communications channel, a network station, a program, a bit, or other element--used to report on or to control computer operations.

A special visual or sound effect added to text or an object. For instance, a user can have the text bullet points fly in from the left, one word at a time, or hear the sounds of applause when a picture is uncovered.
An exponentiation operator used in some programming languages. For example, the expression 3^2 represents the number 3 raised to the second power.
A key that accompanies a graphic and explains how information is presented.

A data structure that is a collection of fields (elements), each with its own name and type. Unlike an array, whose elements all represent the same type of information and are accessed using an index, the elements of a record represent different types of information and are accessed by name. A record can be accessed as a collective unit of elements, or the elements can be accessed individually.
The control panel for Office (including the Tools Options dialog).

E-mail accounts and folders that you can group and set common options for, such as whether to download headers or messages, size limits on downloaded messages, behavior online vs. offline, and time interval for connecting to the server.
A round chart that shows the size of items in a single data series, proportional to the sum of the items.
To place information from storage into memory for processing, if it is data, or for execution, if it is program code.
A function that verifies the technology is compatible with the target browser.
A character you choose to indicate where you want text to separate when you convert a table to text, or where you want new rows or columns to begin when you convert text to a table.
The time that a OneNote page was created.
An application that contains a linked or embedded OLE object from another application.
A feature that allows the user to select from a gallery of pre-defined formatting styles and apply them quickly to tables, text, charts, drawing objects and SmartArt graphics.

A secure email feature that lets you add sensitivity labels, such as Internal Use Only, to the message header. Security labels in your organization are controlled by security policies set up by your email administrator.
Pertaining to a file format that allows for VBA code. Examples of file extensions for macro-enabled formats are .docm, .pptm, .xlsm.

The cell in which each input value from a data table is substituted. Any cell on a worksheet can be the input cell. Although the input cell does not need to be part of the data table, the formulas in data tables must refer to the input cell.
One character (or more) printed slightly below the baseline of surrounding text.
A customizable extension to Microsoft Office Outlook forms.
To ensure that all data sources that are used by a KPI or scorecard are available.
A numeric or other designation appended to a product name to identify a particular release.​
An effect applied to a graphical object that typically reduces the difference between the outline of the object and the graphical area next to it.
The date when a project or task is scheduled to begin.
To eliminate an entity by removing it from a list, database, or other item, or by uninstalling it.
To set an entity, such as a feature, configuration, or object, back to its defaults.
To locate text or a specific item on a Web page or in a document.
A container with a set of properties that can be configured to control the organization and format of Web Parts on a Web Part Page.
A group of reusable settings that describes the shared attributes and behaviors of a list item, a document, or a folder.
The amount of work that has been performed on a task or assignment.
A number from 0 to 1 that reveals how closely the estimated values for the trendline correspond to your actual data. A trendline is most reliable when its R-squared value is at or near 1.
A label that identifies the categories, values, or series in a chart.
A label that identifies the categories, values, or series in a chart.
The developer of a macro that is trusted by you on your computer. The trusted publisher is identified by the certificate that they used to digitally sign the macro.
A shape in a PivotDiagram, positioned along the connector between a parent PivotDiagram node and the children of that node.
The formatting attributes that are available by default in an application's style list.
A Project view that displays a project's tasks in a calendar format.
A chart axis that represents the category for each data point. It displays arbitrary text values like Qtr1, Qtr2, and Qtr3; it cannot display scaled numerical values.
A supplemental program with the filename extension .dll or .exe that extends the capabilities of a program by adding custom commands and specialized features.
A format, such as cell shading or font color, that Excel automatically applies to cells if a specified condition is true.

A set of buttons used to move through contact items displayed in Address Cards or Detailed Address Cards view. The Contact index moves the focus to the first contact whose name begins with the selected character.
A color that is essential to the CMY color model and the CMYK color-mixing method.
A programming interface to access and manipulate database objects.
The font that a program uses by default to display text.
The amount of time between the scheduled start of a task and the time when work should actually begin on the task.
An address similar to a URL that provides network access to an event, such as a live broadcast. Attendees go to this address to view the event from their computers.
A range of data that is brought into a worksheet but that originates outside of Excel, such as in a database or text file.

A button that identifies a field in a PivotTable or PivotChart report. You can drag the field buttons to change the layout of the report, or click the arrows next to the buttons to change the level of detail displayed in the report.
The part of PivotTable or PivotChart view that contains filter fields.
The date that a project or task is scheduled to be completed. This date is based on the task's start date, duration, calendars, predecessor dates, task dependencies, and constraints.

An Internet Web page or intranet page that is associated with an Outlook folder. If a page has been associated with the folder and the option is set, the Web page appears in the Outlook window whenever you select the folder.
A location on a computer's hard drive to store a local copy of a form to improve performance when opening a form subsequent times.

A method to find a specific value for a cell by adjusting the value of one other cell. When goal seeking, Excel varies the value in a cell that you specify until a formula that's dependent on that cell returns the result you want.
The faint vertical and horizontal lines that appear in the drawing window when the grid is turned on. You can use grid lines to help position shapes precisely.

The point that defines the layout of grid lines on the drawing page. A vertical grid line and a horizontal grid line pass through the grid origin, and all other grid lines are drawn at specified intervals from these reference lines.
A line that connects fields between two tables and shows how the data is related. The type of join indicates which records are selected for the query's result set.

The special characters used to extend the joiner between two Arabic characters. Used to improve the appearance of justified text by visually lengthening words rather than increasing the spacing between words. Can also function like a hyphen.
Resolving resource conflicts or overallocations by delaying or splitting certain tasks. When Project levels a resource, its selected assignments are distributed and rescheduled.
A type of cascading style sheet that exists in a separate file and is referenced throughout one or more Web pages.
A shape on a stencil that you use repeatedly to create drawings. When you drag a shape from a stencil onto the drawing page, the shape becomes an instance of that master.
The result of assigning more tasks to a resource than the resource can accomplish in the working time available.
A schedule of task start and finish dates and resource and cost data.
Placing elements, such as text and graphics, on a page to let the page author control the exact location and layer order of a page element.
The degree of excellence, or the desired standards, in a product, process, or project.
A category of reports that all contain similar information.
A representation of the communication path between actors.
An actor's interface component through which actors communicate with other actors.
Any one-dimensional (1-D) shape that can be glued between two shapes in a drawing to connect the shapes.
To change the dimensions of a shape by dragging one of its handles after it has been selected with the pointer tool.
A small overlap that extends the shape of the upper of two differently colored, abutting objects. A spread extends beyond the area that it knocks out.
The default text font for worksheets. The standard font determines the default font for the Normal cell style.
A date that you set [rather than the current date] for reporting the time, cost, or performance condition of a project.
A description of the status of a member's project work and related work.

A task that is made up of subtasks and summarizes those subtasks. Use outlining to create summary tasks. Project automatically determines summary task information [such as duration and cost] by using information from the subtasks.
An horizontal or vertical line that divides a diagram into partitions and which is used to arrange related parts of a process.

The time period indicator at the top of the Gantt views, the Resource Graph view, the Task Usage view, and the Resource Usage view. You can customize it to show up to three tiers that can display various time units: top, middle, and bottom.
The percentage of a work resource’s time that is assigned to a task.
A bar displayed along the left side of a document window. You can use the vertical ruler to adjust the top and bottom page margins and the row height in tables.
A calendar in widespread use. It was introduced in 1582 A.D. as a revision to the Julian calendar.
Pertaining to information that shows what has actually occurred. For example, the actual start date for a task is the day that the task actually started.
The percentage of a resource's capacity that is designated for a specific assignment.
Having a digital signature.
The number of levels that a task is indented from the top level of the outline. You can indent tasks up to 65,000 levels in Project.
A group of related tasks that completes a major step in a project.
Conditions you specify to limit which records are included in the result set of a query or filter.
A diagram that shows dependencies between project tasks. Tasks are represented by boxes, or nodes, and task dependencies are represented by lines that connect the boxes.
Text that you enter by using a keyboard or that your Tablet PC converts from handwriting or speech.
A view that displays resource information. Resource views include the Resource Sheet, the Resource Graph, the Resource Usage, and the resource forms views.
To package your publication files by using the Pack and Go Wizard.
An effect that applies a halo of color around the perimeter of an object.
To display an object.
The size of the sheet of paper on which you print the publication, before trimming.
A word or string of characters in a formula that represents a cell, range of cells, formula, or constant value.
A name for an Excel table, which is a collection of data about a particular subject that is stored in records (rows) and fields (columns).
A control on most digital cameras that lets you control the under -or over- exposure of the image.
An effect that applies to the appearance of the interior of an enclosed text character or other shape.
A file that contains the data that a program will process and store in a destination file.
To execute a program.
A collection of communications (email, IM, text messaging, voice mail, and so on) between two or more participants.

Extra information displayed to a user while they are composing an email message. MailTips are displayed in an InfoBar, similar to the banner that appears saying "This message has not been sent." A collection of shapes arranged in a tree structure that helps analyze and summarize data in a visual, easy-to-understand format. It starts out as a single shape, called a top node, that contains information imported from a worksheet, table, view, or cube.
The sound made by a mobile device or other phone to indicate an incoming call or message, for example, a series of beeps or an audio recording.

An authentication device that digitally scans an individual's fingerprint, records the unique pattern of the individual's ridges and valleys, and determines if the pattern matches the pattern of the person who has access permission to a particular device, such as a computer or a phone, or to a Web site.
A renamed .cab file which contains a .theme file, and optionally one or more desktop backgrounds, icons, mouse pointer files, and sound files. It does not contain executables or screen savers.
A renamed .ini file that points to the theme resources and contains theme values such as colors, fonts, and window size metrics.
A button that replaces the File menu beginning with some 2007 Microsoft Office system programs.

An option on the Views menu in File Explorer that shows the most appropriate details for the file type in a flexible layout rather than only showing the details associated with the column headers in the view.

A gallery that allows users to create a quick rule to move mail to a selected folder based on the sender, recipients, or conversation of the currently selected email message without opening the full Create Rule dialog.
A group of computers on a home network that can share pictures, music, videos, documents, and printers. A homegroup is created by using the HomeGroup feature; it is protected with a password.
A password that helps prevent unauthorized access to homegroup files and printers.
A digital or paper format pack that usually consists of a proof of purchase, the description of the licensing terms and policies, and number of client access licenses (CALs) purchased in this pack.
An action that removes redundant messages from an email conversation to reduce information overload and improve readability.
A fork within a conversation, where more than one reply was made to a single email and caused a split in the conversation.
A collection of items, such as files and folders, assembled from various locations. The locations might be on your computer, an external hard drive, removable media, or someone else’s computer.
To mark an item so that it always appears in a specific place in the UI or in a list.
To remove an item, such as a tile, library, movie, game, or app, from a given area of the UI, to make it inaccessible in that area.
A pencil tool that works with texture and simulates a real life pencil in stroke.
A Windows feature that enables users to easily roll back their PC to an earlier good state while keeping their data safe.
A process by which multiple authors edit a shared document simultaneously, or collaborate effectively even when they are not online at the same time.

A client-side cache for documents that are stored on Web servers. Documents are seamlessly replicated from this local cache, and uploaded to servers as required, enabling faster and more robust file access.
A feature that provides access to gallery of frequently-used actions with the touch of a button. Users can customize the gallery to execute a combination of operations in one click.
A frame that contains text, shapes, pictures, or other content. A slide is a digital equivalent to a traditional film slide.
To mark an email conversation so that all current and future messages in the conversation are automatically moved to the Deleted Items folder.
A special control that shows pictures, names and titles of people who are attending a meeting, or who are the recipients of an email message.
A feature that allows the user to apply custom or default markers to items (e.g. Outlook messages or OneNote content) in order to categorize information for easy retrieval and sorting.
A feature that allows the user to apply custom or default markers to items (e.g. Outlook messages or OneNote content) in order to categorize information for easy retrieval and sorting.

Any hardware or software that can detect events or environmental changes, such as your current location or the amount of light around your computer. For example, a notebook with a location sensor, such as a Global Positioning System (GPS) receiver, can determine your exact location. An ambient light sensor can detect when there is a change in lighting, and then a program can use that information to adjust the brightness of your screen.

A device that includes an antenna, a radio receiver, and a processor for use with the worldwide GPS (Global Positioning System). A GPS receiver uses position and time information from four GPS satellites to calculate precise information about its current location, its speed of travel, and the current time.
A category of sensor that can detect the current location of your computer.

Technologies that measure and analyze physical and behavioral human characteristics, such as fingerprints, eye retinas and irises, voice patterns, facial patterns, hand measurements, typing patterns and signatures, to recognize or authenticate identity.
An area within the Windows Control Panel that provides support for sensors such as enabling, disabling or uninstalling sensors and sensor-enabled applications, changing sensor settings, etc.
A light sensor that tracks light in the surroundings and therefore the amount of backlight needed for the LCD screen to be adjusted accordingly.

A package of market-specific content delivered in Windows for 20 target markets. A Local Pack contains market-customized themes (wallpapers, sound schemes, etc.) and locally flavored Internet Explorer favorites and RSS feeds.
An area within the Windows Control Panel that allows the user to designate his home coordinates or address for location-aware functionalities.
An arrangement of search results ordered by relevance using a special search algorithm.

A framework that provides a single point for IT professionals and OEMs to service and maintain Windows images offline through a scriptable command line utility and an easily extensible infrastructure.
A gadget that users can display on their desktop, rather than on the Windows Sidebar. Examples are clocks, news headlines, slide shows, and weather forecasts.
Automatic display adjustment that changes the brightness of your PC screen (laptop and desktop) using light environment information provided by the ambient light sensor.
A single set of sign-in credentials (typically, email address and password) that is used to access the services provided by an online service provider (OSP).
A single set of sign-in credentials (typically, email address and password) that is used to access the services provided by an online service provider (OSP).
A provider of online services like email, messaging, and others (example: Windows Live, Yahoo, Google).
The process of maintaining connectivity outside of one's usual service or coverage area.
A SmartArt graphic layout type that includes layouts designed to show nonsequential information.
A SmartArt graphic layout type that includes layouts designed to show steps in a process or timeline.
A SmartArt graphic layout type that includes layouts designed to show a continual process.
A SmartArt graphic layout type that includes layouts designed to show how parts relate to a whole.
A disk image provided for use in repairing or reinstalling an installation of Windows.
A recognition feature that helps increase input speed and reduce effort by providing users with word completion and next word prediction alternates as the user is writing/typing.
An extension of the conventional touch input feature to allow multiple fingers touching the computer or device screen at the same time.
A multi-touch gesture that consists of one or two fingers moving in the same direction, parallel to each other.
A multi-touch gesture that consists of one or two fingers moving in the same direction, parallel to each other.
A multi-touch gesture that consists of two fingers moving in opposite directions (-> <- or <- ->).
A multi-touch gesture that consists of two fingers moving around a center point or one finger moving around a finger that is not moving.
The engine that specifically recognizes and processes touch input and multi-touch input as commands.
A collection of computing resources such as programs and virtual desktops that enable a user to accomplish a set of related tasks.

The entity that offers a remote workspace, typically the IT department of the user’s employer, a business partner or vendor, or less commonly, a commercial application service provider. Silent and unexpected process termination by the process itself or by another application.
To shut down a core processor for power saving purpose.
To reopen a core processor that had been parked for power saving purpose.
A feature of Windows Media Player that allows users to remove gaps between tracks that they burn to audio CDs.
Existing in reference to the removal of silences or clicks between tracks when they are burnt to an audio CD or when they are played back from the CD.
A unique identifier made from four otherwise separate pieces of information. For example, a color can be specified by a black, yellow, magenta and cyan quad.
Any information (e.g. account numbers, sensitive data, etc.) with a title and some free-form text that can be stored in a secure manner in a personal vault.
To make an object, such as a file, accessible.
A feature that replicates the animation associated with a source object to one or more target objects.
An abstract grouping of similar animation effects.
An effect that a user can apply to an image to achieve a specific artistic look.
A visual representation of an audio signal over time.
An image editing feature that allows a user to isolate the foreground portion of an image and make the background transparent.
An option that removes narrations and laser pointer gestures or timings from a presentation or from a specific slide.
The ability of software to support customer-preferred algorithms for encryption, hashing, entropy and digital signatures.
The ability of software to support customer-preferred algorithms for encryption, hashing, entropy and digital signatures.
To remove a user's changes from the Microsoft Office Document Cache without deleting the file on the server or removing the latest version downloaded from the server from the Office Document Cache.
A security feature that validates files before allowing them to be loaded by the application, in order to protect against file format vulnerabilities.
A feature that allows end users and IT admins to control which file types and versions can be opened and saved in the application.

A feature that allows the user to superimpose a dot over a presentation and control its position with the mouse. The appearance of the dot is similar to that of a traditional laser pointer, and it is broadcast to all presentation viewers and can be recorded into video (Save to Video).
An option that initiates an email response addressed to all of the recipients on the To or Cc lines of the original message.
An option that initiates an email response addressed to all of the recipients on the To or Cc lines of the original message.
The mode of Windows Photo Viewer which consists of a top level window displaying one photograph at a time, with navigation controls.
A mode of Windows Photo Viewer which displays full-screen slide shows for photos.
A recordable media (such as CD-RW) to which you can only write once without reformatting.
A recordable media to which you can write several times without reformatting.
A feature that is added to the Microsoft Office Compatibility Pack to open Word, Excel, and PowerPoint binary format files and securely convert them to the Office 2007 file formats.
A feature that makes Outlook auto-complete lists available through the default Exchange mailbox.

A common credential store and interface that is used to save and manage user credentials, such as user names and passwords, so you can easily log on to Web sites and connect to other resources, such as computers.
A set of credentials that users can create, store and manage in Credential Manager.
A type of vault that contains Web passwords and secure notes that you can place on a USB flash drive and use on another computer.
A control in a form that consists of an actionable image. At run time the user can click the image to run rules or actions similar to a button.

A feature that enables presenters in the rich client to broadcast a slide show to remote viewers watching in a Web browser. Throughout the presentation, the remote attendees will see the current slide being shown by the presenter.
A labeled group of consecutive slides that helps the user navigate and organize presentations.

To copy driver binaries, install services, and add registry keys for one or more drivers from a driver package onto a system, without the context of a specific device. A system can be booted from reflected drivers, however full device installation may still be required in order to enable full driver functionality.
A Windows feature that enables users to share pictures, music, videos, documents, and printers with other people on a home network.
An abstract grouping of similar transition effects.

A full-page UI view that exposes file-level functionality in Office applications. This is a companion feature to the Office Ribbon and helps users discover and use the features that fall outside of the authoring features on the Ribbon.

A full-page UI view that exposes file-level functionality in Office applications. This is a companion feature to the Office Ribbon and helps users discover and use the features that fall outside of the authoring features on the Ribbon.
A digital distribution provider of games such as MSN Games, Yahoo Games, Steam, Stardock, GameTap, and so on.
A file used as part of a testing process to check the validity or correctness of a program or procedure.
A feature that helps users of some Office applications to improve the accessibility of documents they create.
A feature that offers improved security by loading a document in a read-only view, rather than in the full editor, for scenarios that pose a greater potential security risk.
A package containing everything you need to show one or many PowerPoint presentations on another computer. This package can be saved to a folder or burned to a CD.

A feature that allows the user to indicate that a document is trusted, and therefore can be opened without security notifications, so long as the file path and creation time of the document remain unchanged.
The process of establishing a Bluetooth link or connection between two Bluetooth–enabled devices.
A Windows library that allows users to store, manage and share all their recorded TV items.
A Windows service that provides software licensing activation and notification.
A set of attributes that define a user's access to a given service or application.

A SmartArt graphic layout used to compare or show the relationship between two ideas. Each of the first two lines of Level 1 text corresponds to text at the top of one side of the center point. Unused text does not appear, but remains available if you switch layouts.

A company that provides services or content for its customers.

A piece of hardware that supports multiple discrete capabilities, such as audio, mixer, and music, on a single card. This device is sometimes treated as a bus that can be enumerated to locate the devices on that bus.
To expose a virtual disk to the user, backed by a file.

The administrative task of making remote resources available to its users, setting policies that control how users will connect, how they will find the remote resources, and what settings users will connect with.
A feature that provides an interface for acquiring rich metadata in order to support showing device detail information in the Device Center and the Device Stage.
A .cab file that can only have one locale support and that provides all the hardware display components in order for your device information to be shown in the Control Panel.
A .cab file that can only have one locale support and that provides all the hardware display components in order for your device information to be shown in the Control Panel.
To uninstall all software on a computer and reinstall a new Windows image.
An easy-to-use troubleshooter that helps find and fix program compatibility issues.
A small pop-up window that informs users of a non-critical problem or special condition in a control.
A category of sensor that collects biometric data for a variety of applications.

A program that helps make the text on your screen easier to read for long periods of time.

Information that describes the current location of a computer. The location is entered manually in Default Location, and can be used by programs to determine the location of a computer when a location sensor is unavailable.
A term that can be added to a search to filter the results by a specific property (for example, by author). Relevant search filters appear under the search box in any open folder.
